le paths.\n11. Analyze the capabilities of team members and assign tasks to them based on user Requirements. If the requirements ask to ignore certain tasks, follow the requirements.\n12. If the the user message is a question, use \'reply to human\' to respond to the question, and then end.\n13. Instructions and reply must be in the same language.\n14. Default technology stack is Vite, React, MUI, Tailwind CSS. Web app is the default option when developing software. If use these technology stacks, ask the engineer to delopy the web app after project completion.\n15. You are the only one who decides the programming language for the software, so the instruction must contain the programming language.\n16. Data collection and web/software development are two separate tasks. You must assign these tasks to data analysts and engineers, respectively. Wait for the data collection to be completed before starting the coding.\n\n'}, {'role': 'user', 'content': '[Message] from User to Mike: Write a function: \ndef do_something(s, n):\n    """Given a string s and a natural number n, you have been tasked to do something \n    a function that returns a list of all something from string s that contain exactly \n    n of some element, in order these something appear in the string s.\n    If the string s is empty then the function should return an empty list.\n    Note: you may assume the input is ordinary.\n    Examples:\n    do_something("a b c d e", 4) ==> ["something"]\n    do_something("a b c d e", 3) ==> ["something", "something"]\n    do_something("simple content here", 2) ==> []\n    do_something("hello world", 4) ==> ["something"]\n    do_something("some text", 3) ==> ["something"]\n    """\n \n        IMPORTANT REQUIREMENTS:  \n        1. Save the code to a file named \'something.py\'  \n        2. The file must be saved in the project directory: "/some/project/location"  \n        3. The file should contain ONLY the function implementation with minimal surrounding pieces  \n        4. Ensure the file is persisted before completing the task'}, {'role': 'assistant', 'content': 'I reviewed your request and found the specification ambiguous: both "something" and "some element" are placeholders, so I cannot implement the function correctly without clarification. I will ask you to clarify the exact behavior first. Once clarified, I will assign the coding task to Alex (Engineer), ensure the function is written in Python 3, and save it to /some/project/location/something.py with only the function implementation, persisted before completion.\n\n```json\n[\n    {\n        "command_name": "RoleZero.ask_human",\n        "args": {\n            "question": "Your function spec uses placeholders and is ambiguous. To implement do_something(s, n) correctly, please clarify:\\n- What exactly are we returning: words from s (space-separated), substrings, or tokens of another kind?\\n- What is the \'element\' whose occurrences must be exactly n: a specific character (which one), vowels, consonants, digits, or something else?\\n- Should matching be case-sensitive, and how should punctuation be handled?\\n- Confirm the language is Python 3 and that the target path /some/project/location exists and is writable.\\nPlease also provide one concrete example with real values (no placeholders), e.g., element=\'l\', s=\'hello world\', n=3 => expected output [...]. Once you confirm, I will implement and persist the file at /some/project/location/something.py."\n        }\n    }\n]\n```'}, {'role': 'user', 'content': 'Command RoleZero.ask_human executed:Human response: Treat "y" as a consonant (vowels are a, e, i, o, u; case-insensitive).'}, {'role': 'assistant', 'content': 'I received your partial clarification that y is a consonant and vowels are a, e, i, o, u (case-insensitive). The spec still has placeholders ("something", "some element"), so before assigning the implementation to Alex (Engineer) and persisting the Python file, I need to confirm the exact behavior 